<DOC><DOCNO> AP890602-0230 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-89 0210EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-02 0739</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0771</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The productivity of American workers slippedin the first quarter while unit labor costs shot up more than 6percent on an annual basis, the government said in a reportanalysts cited as proof both of a slowing economy and stubborninflation.   The Labor Department's revised figures for the first threemonths of the year showed a 1.1 percent decline in non-farmbusiness productivity at an annual rate, down from the 0.5 percentgain reported in preliminary first-quarter data issued last month.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Carl Icahn ended a long and contentiousassociation with Texaco Inc., selling a Wall Street-record 42.32million share block of the oil company's stock.   The shares sold for $49 each Thursday, making the entire blockworth more than $2.07 billion. Texaco spokeswoman Anita Larsen saidthe shares were bought by the investment firms Shearson LehmanHutton Inc., Salomon Brothers Inc. and Goldman Sachs andamp; Co.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   High interest rates depressed the rate ofprivate construction in April, but the government said that totalconstruction spending rose a weak 0.1 percent due to an upturn inwork on public projects.   The Commerce Department on Thursday reported a total increase innew spending to $414.9 billion on a seasonally adjusted annual rateafter declines of three consecutive months. That was 4.7 percentabove a year earlier.   The last time construction spending fell for three straightmonths had been just before the start of the 1981-82 recession.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Major U.S. retailers reported sluggish Maysales, fresh evidence that consumers have curbed spending becauseof heavy debt loads.   Tallies released Thursday varied depending on the type ofretailer, but industry-wide results looked weak, analysts said.</TEXT><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC ministers are getting ready tonegotiate a new oil production strategy, amid price and outputdemands aimed at changing the current cartel accord that has seen arise in world crude prices.   Ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum ExportingCountries were gathering at their Vienna, Austria headquarters fora mid-year meeting set to begin Monday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush's plan to keep $50 billion inborrowed Sandamp;L rescue funds ``off budget'' to avoid swelling thefederal deficit was rejected by a House committee whose chairmanlabeled the approach ``voodoo accounting.''   With only one Democrat supporting Bush's plan, the HouseGovernment Operations Committee voted 22-15 on Thursday to includethe initial $50 billion taxpayer share of the bailout as part ofthe federal budgets for this year and fiscal 1990 and 1991.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Representatives of 151 governments in theWorld Bank will make about $10 billion available over the nextthree years to support Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady's planfor cutting debt in the Third World.   Under guidelines announced Thursday after more than two days ofclosed-door board meetings, $375 million of that new money will beavailable to apply to Mexico's existing $108 billion debt.</TEXT><DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines says is part of aninvestment group led by Los Angeles investor Alfred Checchi thathas submitted a friendly bid to buy NWA Inc., the parent ofNorthwest Airlines.   KLM spokesman Peter Wellhuener said Thursday the Dutch stateairliner has ``a commitment to an American investment group headedby Mr. Alfred Checchi to take an indirect interest'' in the companybidding for Northwest. No other details were released.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The New York Stock Exchange has approved fortrading a portfolio of 500 stocks priced at about $5 million perunit billed as the first of its kind to provide ownership of eachof the component equities.   Each portfolio unit will include 126,000 shares of stock basedon the Standard andamp; Poor's 500 stock index, ranging from 3,100 sharesof Exxon Corp. to nine of the Monarch Machine Tool Co. based oncurrent caluclations.</TEXT><NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE><TEXT>   Stock prices gained ground Thursday in a session dominated by arecord-sized transaction in Texaco shares just as the marketclosed. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.48 pointsto 2,490.63.   The dollar finished mixed against major foreign currencies.   Bond prices were little changed in advance of the government'sMay employment report.   Feeder cattle futures prices soared; grains and soybeans endedmostly higher; copper futures prices dropped sharply while preciousmetals rose; and energy futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>